passages.text: Kehua Data Co. (002335.SZ)2025 largely in line, solid domestic outlook, overseas expansion in progress; Maintain Neutral on valuation

Kehua reported 2Q25 results with revenue/gross profit/EBIT/net profit at Rmb2,516mn/Rmb567mn/Rmb218mn/Rmb175mn, \(- 1\% / + 7\% / + 24\% / + 15\%\) yoy, and \(- 1\% / - 13\% / + 7\% / - 13\%\) vs. GSe, largely in line excluding the credit impairment losses of Rmb47mn. GPM/Opm/NPM arrived at \(23\% /9\% /7\%\) in 2Q25, \(+2\mathrm{pp} / + 2\mathrm{pp} / + 1\mathrm{pp}\) yoy, and - 3pp/+1pp/- 1pp vs. GSe. We tweak 2025- 30E net income forecasts by \(- 1\%\) on average to reflect the results. Our updated 12m TP is Rmb42.6 (from Rmb42.8 previously). Maintain Neutral as the stock is trading at \(34\times /28\times 2026E / 2027E\) P/E against \(14\%\) 2027- 30E earnings CAGR.

Data center products and smart power products sales was Rmb784mn/Rmb439mn respectively \((+34\% / - 23\%)\) yoy),totaling Rmb1,224mn \((+6\%)\) yoy) vs. domestic peer Kstar's comparable business sales at Rmb1,299mn \((+8\%)\) yoy) in 1H25. GPM was overall stable yoy.We expect \(30\%\) yoy growth for this segment in 2H25E driven by solid data center demand growth and Kehua's order delivery schedule.

Overseas sales contribution was limited in 1H25, but company is actively expanding overseas customer base, now in sampling stages with data center customers from multiple regions (including North America), expecting more business progress in 2026E, per management.

Domestic demand growth has been solid in 2025 YTD, and Kehua maintains high wallet share with Tencent's data center orders while also serving other internet and telecom customers. New product development: For power infrastructure, Kehua has seen its HVDC (high- voltage direct current) products adopted by customers including Tencent, and they are in R&D for next- generation HVDC technologies and SST (solid- state

transformers). On the cooling side, they provide liquid- cooled modular data centers and racks for AI applications, mainly serving Chinese telecom operators currently. Kehua has its in- house C (coolant distribution units) but we believe most of its other liquid cooling components are procured from third- party suppliers.

Renewable energy product sales was Rmb1,852mn in 1H25 (- 4% yoy) and mainly came from selling energy storage systems (ESS) and power conversion systems (PCS). Segment G improved by 0.6pp/0.9pp to 17.5% in 1H25 mainly due to higher overseas contribution with overseas sales recording Rmb230mn (+53% yoy from a low base), and management believes the segment GPM improvement trend can sustain going forward.
IDC service sales was Rmb439mn (flat yoy) with GPM dropping to \(20.8\%\) (vs. \(25.8\% /20.9\%\) in 1H24/2H24), mainly affected by depreciation costs of newly deployed projects.

Earnings and TP revision: We tweak 2025E- 2030E net profit by - 1% on average to reflect the results. Accordingly, our 12m TP moves to Rmb42.6 (vs. Rmb42.8) on our revisions and 1% total shares outstanding increase in 2Q25, still based on 25x 2026E P/E. Maintain Neutral. Downside risks: (1) Lower- than- expected data center revenue growth; (2) Lower- than- expected new energy revenue outlook; (3) Lower- than- expected new energy margin. Upside/downside risks: (1) Better/worse- than- expected data center customer capex; (2) Faster/Slower- than- expected product expansion/market share gain progress; (3) Price competition on data center/renewable energy products.

Investment thesis: Kehua Data is a leader in China's Uninterruptible Power Supply (UPS) market, with globally competitive power management products supported by a technology- focused and stable core management team. Since the early 2010s, Kehua has been broadening its offerings beyond stand- alone UPS products to tailor- made power management solutions for various industries, notably rail transit, data centers, electronics, oil & gas, base stations, etc. Kehua is also the one of the top PCS (Power

Conversion System) makers in China. We expect Kehua to ride on the tailwind of domestic data center capex upcycle given increasing AI applications and increased power demand of data centers. That said, we believe the current share price has factored in the bullish capex growth outlook of end customers. We are Neutral- rated on Kehua given we see a relatively balanced risk/reward considering the current valuation level.

Price target risks & methodology: Our 12m target price of Rmb42.6 is based on 2026E P/E of 25x. Upside/downside risks: (1) Better/worse- than- expected data center customer capex; (2) Faster/Slower- than- expected product expansion/market share gain progress; (3) Price competition on data center/renewable energy products.

The Goldman Sachs Factor Profile provides investment context for a stock by comparing key attributes to the market (i.e. our universe of rated stocks) and its sector peers. The four key attributes depicted are: Growth, Financial Returns, Multiple (e.g. valuation) and Integrated (a composite of Growth, Financial Returns and Multiple). Growth, Financial Returns and Multiple are calculated by using normalized ranks for specific metrics for each stock. The normalized ranks for the metrics are then averaged and converted into percentiles for the relevant attribute. The precise calculation of each metric may vary depending on the fiscal year, industry and region, but the standard approach is as follows:

Growth is based on a stock's forward- looking sales growth, EBITDA growth and EPS growth (for financial stocks, only EPS and sales growth), with a higher percentile indicating a higher growth company. Financial Returns is based on a stock's forward- looking ROE, ROCE and CROCI (for financial stocks, only ROE), with a higher percentile indicating a company with higher financial returns. Multiple is based on a stock's forward- looking P/E, P/B, price/dividend (P/D), EV/EBITDA, EV/FCF and EV/Debt Adjusted Cash Flow (DACF) (for financial stocks, only P/E, P/B and P/D), with a higher percentile indicating a stock trading at a higher multiple. The Integrated percentile is calculated as the average of the Growth percentile, Financial Returns percentile and (100% - Multiple percentile).

Financial Returns and Multiple use the Goldman Sachs analyst forecasts at the fiscal year- end at least three quarters in the future. Growth uses inputs for the fiscal year at least seven quarters in the future compared with the year at least three quarters in the future (on a per- share basis for all metrics).
For a more detailed description of how we calculate the GS Factor Profile, please contact your GS representative.
